      detailedReview: "I joined NVIDIA 3 years ago as a CUDA compiler engineer. The work is technically fascinating — you're optimizing code that runs on literally every AI training cluster in the world. My refresh this year was wild: 200 additional RSUs at the post-split price, which at current valuation adds ~$80K/yr to my TC.\n\nThe downside? Jensen runs this place like a startup. There's no middle management buffer — he has 60+ direct reports and any of them can pull you into a Saturday review. The 'flat org' sounds good in theory but in practice it means priorities shift fast and you need to be comfortable with ambiguity.\n\nDay-to-day, I spend about 60% of my time writing and reviewing CUDA compiler passes, 20% in cross-team design discussions, and 20% debugging performance regressions that customers file. The customer-facing aspect surprised me — when a major cloud provider reports a 5% perf regression on their training workload, it becomes your top priority overnight.\n\nThe Santa Clara campus is fine but nothing special compared to Google/Meta. No free dinner, limited shuttle service. The cafeteria is subsidized but not free. The money makes up for it though — I've never felt the need for free meals when my paycheck looks like this.",
