      detailedReview: "I left Apple (ICT4) for Meta (E5) 2 years ago and it's the best career decision I've made. TC went from $345K to $375K, but more importantly, the autonomy and pace of shipping increased 10x.\n\nAt Apple, I spent 4 months getting a design spec approved. At Meta, I shipped a new Instagram feature from idea to production in 3 weeks. The 'move fast' culture isn't just a slogan — the infrastructure supports it. Meta's CI/CD pipeline for iOS is genuinely the most sophisticated I've seen: automated testing, staged rollouts to 1% → 10% → 50% → 100%, instant rollback capabilities.\n\nThe Instagram iOS codebase is a fascinating blend of React Native and native Swift/ObjC. About 60% of screens are React Native (powered by Meta's internal RN fork which is significantly more performant than open-source RN), and 40% are native for performance-critical surfaces like the camera, Stories editor, and video player. Navigating this hybrid architecture is a unique skill.\n\nOne surprise: Meta gives iOS engineers much more product influence than Apple does. At Apple, PMs and designers hand you a spec. At Meta, engineers are expected to push back on designs, propose alternatives, and own the technical-product trade-offs. My PM and I are genuine partners, not manager-and-executor.",
      interviewExperience: "The Meta iOS loop was different from Apple's. 2 coding rounds (Leetcode medium — standard array/tree problems), 1 system design (mobile-specific: 'design Instagram's feed with offline support, pagination, and real-time updates'), 1 behavioral. No 'framework design' round like Apple.\n\nThe mobile system design round is where iOS experience shines. I discussed: data layer architecture (Core Data vs Realm vs custom), network layer (GraphQL with optimistic updates), image caching (multi-tier with memory/disk/CDN), and state management for the feed (MVVM with unidirectional data flow). They loved that I brought up accessibility and performance profiling as first-class concerns.\n\nCompared to Apple's interview: Meta's is less about deep iOS trivia (no 'explain ARC retain cycle resolution in block captures') and more about practical system thinking. I found it easier to prepare for.",
      workLifeBalance: "42-44 hrs/week. The RTO is annoying — 3 days in MPK — but the campus is genuinely nice. The iOS team has 'no meeting Wednesdays' which gives a blessed day of uninterrupted coding. On-call rotation is light for mobile: 1 week per 8 weeks, and pages are rare (maybe once per month across the whole team).\n\nCompared to Apple: Meta is clearly better on WLB. No WWDC crunch, no launch crunch tied to hardware release schedules. The pressure is consistent and manageable rather than Apple's boom-bust cycle around September launches.",
      teamCulture: "Instagram iOS is a mature, well-run team. The codebase is large (~3M lines) but well-maintained with strong coding standards and linting. Code reviews are fast (2-4 hour turnaround) and constructive. There's a healthy mix of React Native and native expertise, and the team values engineers who can work across both.\n\nOne cultural difference from Apple: at Meta, everything is measured. Every feature has engagement metrics, A/B test results, and performance dashboards. This data-driven approach feels more honest than Apple's approach of 'ship what the designer says and hope users like it.' At Meta, you know within a week whether your feature is working.",
