      salaryRange: { min: "$300K", max: "$400K", median: "$345K" },
      detailedReview: "I work on UIKit — yes, it's still alive and powers most of iOS despite SwiftUI's marketing push. TC is around $345K: $210K base, $35K bonus, ~$100K RSUs vesting.\n\nThe secrecy thing isn't exaggerated. I literally cannot tell my spouse what features I'm working on for the next iOS release. Every project has a code name, meetings are compartmentalized, and building access is restricted by project. It's annoying but there's a genuine pride in the big reveal at WWDC when millions of developers see your work for the first time. That moment — when Craig Federighi demos a feature you built — is a unique high.\n\nWhat makes Apple special for an iOS engineer: the attention to detail is extreme. A 1-pixel misalignment in a system UI element will block your PR. A 2ms regression in animation frame time triggers a performance investigation. The code review culture is the most rigorous I've experienced — more thorough than Google's, though slower. Your code ships to every iPhone on Earth, and that weight shapes how you think about quality.\n\nDaily work: 60% coding (Swift and some ObjC for legacy UIKit components), 20% design reviews (working with HI designers on interaction details), 20% performance optimization (profiling with Instruments, optimizing for the full range from iPhone SE to iPhone Pro Max).",
      interviewExperience: "5 rounds: 2 coding (Swift-specific — lots of protocol-oriented programming, value types vs reference types, and concurrency with async/await), 1 system design (iOS-specific: 'design the Photos app sync architecture handling 100K+ photos with offline support and conflict resolution'), 1 framework design ('design a pagination API for UIKit that's backward-compatible and composable'), 1 hiring manager.\n\nThe framework design round is Apple-specific and very hard. They want elegant, forward-compatible API design: How would your API look in 5 years? What if we need to add streaming support? How do you handle deprecation gracefully? I spent 30 minutes just on the public interface before touching implementation details. Apple values API beauty in a way no other company does.\n\nPrep advice: study Apple's own API design patterns. Look at how UIKit and SwiftUI APIs are structured. Read Apple's API Design Guidelines document. If you can design an API that 'feels like Apple designed it,' you'll nail this round.",
      workLifeBalance: "Crunch before WWDC (June) and iPhone launch (September) is real: 55-60 hrs/week for 4-6 weeks each. That's 2-3 months of crunch per year. The rest of the year is genuinely 40-43 hrs. Apple Park is beautiful — the walking paths, the café (though food isn't free like Google), the fitness center. The commute to Cupertino is my biggest quality of life factor — it's 45 min each way for me from SF.\n\nNo remote option for most engineering teams. Apple believes in in-person collaboration and they're not budging. This is the #1 reason I hear for people leaving Apple for Meta or Google.",
      teamCulture: "Very craftsmanship-oriented. Engineers take personal pride in their code — it's not uncommon for someone to spend an extra day polishing an animation curve that 99% of users won't consciously notice. Less 'move fast break things,' more 'measure twice, cut once.' The flip side: things can move slowly. Getting a design spec approved involves HI review, engineering review, privacy review, and accessibility review. A feature that takes 2 weeks to code might take 2 months to ship through all the reviews.\n\nThe people are exceptional. My team includes someone who literally wrote parts of the UIKit framework that every iOS developer uses. Having them review your code is humbling and educational.",
      pros: ["Your code ships to 1B+ devices — career-defining impact", "Extreme craftsmanship culture makes you a better engineer", "Apple Park campus is genuinely stunning", "Deep technical iOS problems that don't exist anywhere else"],
      cons: ["Secrecy culture is socially isolating", "No remote work option", "WWDC and launch crunch periods are brutal", "Cupertino is expensive and suburban — boring compared to SF"],
      advice: "Know Swift inside and out — not just the syntax, but memory management (ARC details, weak/unowned semantics), concurrency (structured concurrency, actors, sendable), and protocol-oriented design patterns. If you can contribute to a Swift open-source project before applying, that's gold on your resume. Also: Apple values depth over breadth. Being a world-class iOS engineer matters more than being a decent iOS + web + backend engineer.",
