      detailedReview: "I've been on the Siri ML team for 6 years, through the transition from the old rule-based system to the current on-device ML approach and now the generative AI push. TC at ICT5 is ~$480K: $250K base, $50K bonus, ~$180K RSUs. Apple's comp at senior levels has improved dramatically in the past 2 years — they were losing too many ML people to Google and OpenAI.\n\nThe Apple Intelligence push has completely transformed my team. We went from a 20-person team maintaining a mature NLU system to a 50-person team building a new generative AI stack from scratch. The scale of investment is unlike anything I've seen in my 6 years here. We have dedicated Apple Silicon team members working on neural engine optimizations specifically for our models.\n\nWhat makes Siri ML unique: everything runs on-device. Our models need to fit in memory alongside every other app, achieve <100ms inference latency, and not destroy the battery. These constraints force incredibly creative ML engineering. We do quantization, distillation, and architecture innovation that's years ahead of what cloud-first companies publish. Some of our techniques have become papers that I'm proud of.\n\nThe downside of Apple ML: the secrecy means we can't participate in the open research community the way Google Brain or FAIR can. My papers go through a 3-month review process before publication. By the time they're published, they feel dated. If academic reputation matters to you, Apple is the wrong choice.",
      interviewExperience: "ICT5 ML loop was 7 rounds over 2 days: 2 ML coding (implement a transformer attention mechanism with KV caching for on-device inference, implement a quantization-aware training loop), 1 ML system design ('design the on-device ML pipeline for Siri intent classification supporting 100+ languages'), 1 general system design, 1 research presentation (present your best paper/project, 45 min + Q&A), 1 leadership, 1 VP chat.\n\nThe research presentation is unique to Apple ICT5+ ML roles. They want to see not just what you built, but how you think about research taste — what problems are worth solving, what approaches are elegant, what trade-offs matter. I presented my work on efficient attention mechanisms for on-device inference, and the discussion afterward was the most intellectually stimulating interview experience I've had.",
      workLifeBalance: "ICT5 has more control over schedule. I average 43-45 hrs/week, with crunch around iOS launches (50+ hrs for 3-4 weeks). The senior level means I can push back on unreasonable timelines, though WWDC deadlines are sacred and non-negotiable regardless of your level.\n\nI WFH illegally (don't tell Tim) about 1 day per week by 'working from a different building' on campus. Many senior engineers do this — the official policy is 3 days in office but enforcement varies by org.",
      teamCulture: "The Siri ML team has changed dramatically with the AI push. The old guard (NLU rule system experts) and the new guard (LLM/generative AI people) don't always see eye to eye. There's tension between 'reliability and control' (old approach) and 'capability and flexibility' (new approach). Navigating this requires diplomacy.\n\nAt ICT5, you're expected to set technical direction. I own the model architecture decisions for our intent classification system, which serves billions of queries daily. The autonomy is real but the accountability is equally real — when my model regresses, I'm the one in a room with the VP explaining what happened.",
      pros: ["On-device ML constraints drive genuine innovation", "Apple Silicon + ML co-design is uniquely powerful", "ICT5 comp is finally competitive with FAANG", "Building AI that runs on 1B+ devices is career-defining"],
      cons: ["Secrecy kills academic reputation and open-source participation", "3-month paper review process makes published work feel dated", "Cultural tension between old Siri and new AI teams", "No remote option — Cupertino or nothing"],
      advice: "For ML roles at Apple: on-device efficiency is the differentiator. If you have experience with model compression, quantization, or neural architecture search, you're exactly what they want. Pure research chops help but Apple values practical ML engineering — your model needs to run on an iPhone SE, not just a DGX cluster. Prepare a research presentation that showcases both technical depth and practical impact.",
