      detailedReview: "Most people don't know Apple has a massive server-side engineering org. I work on iCloud backend — the infrastructure that syncs Photos, Notes, Health data, and more across 2B+ Apple devices. TC is ~$340K: $200K base, $30K bonus, ~$110K RSUs.\n\nThe scale is staggering: iCloud stores exabytes of user data across multiple data centers globally. Our sync protocol handles billions of operations per day with conflict resolution that needs to 'just work' even when devices are offline for weeks. The engineering challenges are genuinely distributed systems problems at a scale that rivals AWS internals.\n\nSurprise #1: Apple's backend stack is primarily Java and Kotlin, not Swift. We run on a custom Kubernetes-like orchestration system (not actual Kubernetes). The internal tooling is a mixed bag — some things are world-class (our deployment pipeline), others feel like they were built in 2010 and never updated (monitoring dashboards).\n\nSurprise #2: privacy engineering is not just a talking point. Every feature I build goes through a privacy review where a dedicated privacy engineer examines data flows. We've scrapped features that worked perfectly because the data access pattern didn't meet Apple's privacy bar. This constraint makes engineering harder but also makes you a better privacy-aware engineer.",
