      detailedReview: "I work on the Stripe Dashboard — the web application that millions of businesses use to manage payments, view analytics, configure their integration, and handle disputes. TC is ~$330K: $200K base + ~$130K RSUs. Slightly lower than backend counterparts at the same level, which is a known FE-vs-BE pay gap at Stripe.\n\nThe Dashboard is a massive React + TypeScript application with some of the most sophisticated data visualization work in the industry. We render real-time payment data, complex financial charts, and interactive API logs for merchants processing millions of transactions. Performance is critical — merchants are often making time-sensitive decisions based on what our dashboard shows them.\n\nStripe's FE stack is built on a custom design system called 'Sail' (internally) which is the basis for Stripe's public UI components. Working on Sail means your work impacts both the Dashboard and all of Stripe's public-facing checkout and payment UIs. The attention to design detail rivals Apple — every pixel, every animation curve, every color choice goes through a design review process.\n\nThe FE community at Stripe is smaller than at Meta or Google (~80 FE engineers total) which means you get visibility and impact quickly. I shipped a redesigned Analytics dashboard 4 months after joining that now has 500K+ monthly active merchants using it. At a bigger company, I'd still be ramping up.",
      interviewExperience: "Stripe FE interviews: 2 practical coding rounds (build a small interactive React component — one was a sortable table, the other was a type-ahead search with debouncing), 1 FE system design ('design the Dashboard's real-time payment feed with filtering, search, and CSV export for millions of transactions'), 1 craft interview (pair program on a real Dashboard feature — they evaluate code quality, accessibility, and testing).\n\nThe FE system design is the differentiator. They care about: data fetching strategy (pagination, infinite scroll, caching), state management architecture, accessibility (WCAG compliance is mandatory), performance (bundle size, rendering performance, perceived speed), and error handling (what happens when the API returns unexpected data?).\n\nNo Leetcode. The practical rounds test real-world React skills: component composition, hook design, state management, and CSS layout. If you've built production React apps, you'll feel right at home.",
      workLifeBalance: "42-45 hrs/week. FE teams at Stripe are less on-call-intensive than backend teams since the Dashboard isn't payment-critical infrastructure. On-call is 1 week per 8 weeks and pages are rare — maybe once every 2-3 rotations. The 4-hour focus blocks culture helps a lot with FE work, which requires deep concentration for complex layout and interaction work.\n\nThe design review process can be time-consuming. A single UI change might go through 3 rounds of design feedback before shipping. This is great for quality but can feel slow when you want to iterate quickly.",
      teamCulture: "The FE community at Stripe punches above its weight. We maintain an internal FE blog, run weekly 'FE Guild' meetings where someone presents a deep-dive on a technique, and contribute to Stripe's public technical blog. The culture of learning and sharing is genuine.\n\nDesign-engineering collaboration at Stripe is the best I've experienced. Designers and engineers share Figma files early, iterate together, and ship jointly. There's no 'throw designs over the wall' dynamic. My designer partner and I do weekly pair-design sessions where we prototype together in the browser.",
      pros: ["Your UI is used by millions of businesses daily", "Design system work impacts all of Stripe's products", "Smaller FE community = high visibility and fast impact", "Design-engineering collaboration is genuinely the best in tech"],
      cons: ["FE comp is slightly lower than backend at same level", "Design review process can slow down shipping", "Stripe's custom tooling means less open-source transferability", "Dashboard codebase is large and has legacy patterns"],
      advice: "Build a polished React side project with real attention to design and accessibility. Stripe FE interviews don't test algorithmic puzzle-solving — they test whether you can build beautiful, accessible, performant web applications. Know CSS layout deeply (flexbox, grid, responsive patterns). Understand React's rendering model and performance optimization techniques (memo, useMemo, React.lazy). And importantly: care about design. Stripe engineers who collaborate well with designers get promoted faster.",
